snippet.textDisplay: There was no "big bang." It's awfully arrogant for mankind to make the assumption that we understand how this universe, which we are literally unable to measure in size and scope, began. It has always existed. It's infinite in size and time. We cannot conclude how something we don't understand came to being. The universe is also teaming with extra-terrestrial life, and clearly those entities are either in charge and/or under orders to leave us alone so that we can experience this place. They will intervene if we seek them out. Call them angels, aliens, whatever, but they are friends. They are us. It's self-evident that we existed before coming and will exist after death. You and I have probably already been all over the galaxy. The question is why are you and I here? What's the purpose? If we are spiritual beings having a mortal, physical experience, shouldn't we try to learn why God put us here? (And jointly agreed to come?) To believe we randomly exist, to deny a creator and the need for a Savior--to deny the obvious so that you can go on through life unaccountable for your actions--is the height of pride and a cop-out.
